Quote:and a hydroxyl radical. The latter is a water molecule with one of the hydrogens stripped away, but having left its electron behind, it's water without a proton, in effectNope, that's an ion - a rather common one, as it happens. A hydroxyl radical is water minus the entire hydrogen atom, so the oxygen has an unpaired electron.
